text=(:if [ authgroup @tas || authgroup @admins || equal {$Author} '' ]:)%0a%0a(:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%0a>>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%0a[[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=edit|Edit this page]] \\%0aStatus: {GradebookArticles.{$Name}$:Status} %0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0a----%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a[[!{$:Category}]]%0a%0a!Minderico%0a%0a:Author: sjdutton%0a%0a'''Summary:''' \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aThe Highly Endangered Minderico Language in Portugal%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aMinderico is a language in Portugal, specifically in Minde. Today there are only around 150 speakers of the language, but only 23 of those who are completely fluent According to Ethnologue, the EGIDs level of the language is between 6b and 9, meaning it is an endangered language. There are two reasons for Minderico’s endangerment. Firstly, many people are leaving the town of Minde and are not bringing the language with them. Secondly, Minderico is dominated by Portuguese, which is taught in schools and used in the legal system. This means Minderico is only really used within households. %0a%0aNonetheless, there have been projects to keep Minderico alive. In 2009, The Documentation of Endangered Languages (DOBES) created a project which included transcribing the use of the language, developing a Minderico lexicon, and creating a grammar sketch. The leader of the project Vera Ferreira worked with the Minde community in order to preserve the language. All these efforts better the chances of keeping the Minderico language alive for longer.%0a%0aSources: %0ahttps://www.ethnologue.com/size-and-vitality/drc %0ahttps://www.endangeredlanguages.com/lang/10869?hl=en %0ahttps://dobes.mpi.nl/posters/print/eurasia-minderico-print.pdf %0a%0a[[#contentends]